Thanks Edward I thought I remembered you did those tests on Ochre. Unfortunately I don't have any wood ash. Did you process the material yourself? If so may I ask what method you used? I am currently drying the material out with the idea of slaking it in water so I can sieve the rocks and other material out. I also think I may sinter it to cone 05 to remove any organics. I am slightly concerned that doing that may actually fuse the material because it seems to have some clay content.

Does anyone else have any experience with using raw copper? I usually just buy the green powder in a baggie and I am not sure how they process that. Mechanical? Chemical? We also went swimming in an abandoned copper quarry that hit a spring and filled up with water. I picked up some interesting samples there as well. Vancouver Island is very geologically rich. It's also something of a pottery Paradise. I will probably move out there at some point.

I have added some more pics of the deposit on my blog so check them out at http://fireandmud.blogspot.com/

