Greg,

replace woodash by whiting and it will work.
I have tested about 40 glazes containing &quot;local
red ochre&quot; but they are all over my hard-drive.

I got my ochre from the lady next door whose
uncle owned the mine until his death many years ago.

It is very simple to process
1- Let the stuff dry completely
2-Break the larger bits with something
solid,
3-Sieve it to the granulometry you want,
if you own many.
I am lucky, I was given sieves ranging from 20
to 325 meshes by companies closing down

The samples I got from the lady next door were
relatively fine-grained, so I dry them and sieved
30 and 60 meshes. What went thru 60 also went thru
170.
Therefore I have larger and finer grained ochre.

I believe the method you described is suitable,
it is like washing and sieveing ashes, it should
work.
I would bring your ochre to the red as we say in French,
&quot;amener au rouge&quot;, that is close to quartz inversion,
I mean when the kiln is starting to become red inside;
to get rid of most of the volatiles,
I did not do that with my samples and never had a
volatile-related problem, even if I added large amounts
of the material to my glazes.

Gis la revido,

Edouard Bastarache
