<POSTER> Richard Mahaffey &lt;rickmahaf...@comcast.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-28T01:49:00 </POSTDATE>
Phillip,
Copper wire works great in a Saggar.  I fire to about 1825 F with copper
wire around my pots, I use 42 gauge wire because the mark gets wider
during the firing.  I have also used this same wire under a clear glaze
and I get red and green from it when fired in reduction at cone 10.  you
simply hold the wire in place on the bisque with dots of glaze about
every two inches, then dip the whole pot in the glaze bucket.  Spraying
the glaze will tend to blow the wire around.

If you go to my page at school at :

http://www.tacomacc.edu/home/rmahaffe/contents.htm
then click on my work you can see some of my saggar fired work.

You do have to be careful because when the metalic copper falls onto a
shelf in a cone 10 reduction firing it can kind of eat into a shelf.  I
know this because someone threw a penny into a kiln and we had a black
hole in the shelf that went about 3/8 of an inch deep (mullite shelves)
so I used a chisel to remove the black area hopeing that by doing that
it would not erode the shelf any deeper.

Rick Mahaffey

